<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n05011g"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n05" href="#n05011g">N05 (VI.B.2)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n05all.htm#n05011g"> 11(g)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Let us (II)</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">After making the beasts, cattle, and creeping things, we are told that &ldquo;God said, <mark>Let us</mark> make man in our image, after our likeness.&rdquo; To whom did God say this? Some declare it is the royal style of address. Others find in it the first suggestion of the Trinity. The truth is that the word translated God is Elohim&mdash;literally <mark>Gods</mark>. Originally the Jews were Polytheists. <small> G.W. Foote, <a name="BROM" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#BROM"><cite title="source">Bible Romances</cite></a>, 4th ed. (1922) [The Creation Story] 14</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
